  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalizing financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Implementing customer identification and due diligence programs\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\n4. Penalties:\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Substantial fines\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential imprisonment\n\n5. International Cooperation:\n- Collaboration with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force)\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n\nThese statutes are designed to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities, helping to disrupt criminal financial networks and protect the integrity of the financial system.",
